---
title: 07 streaming algorithms
---

Q: Moving-average state for a fixed window.
A: Circular buffer, running sum, count seen, next index.

---

Q: Streaming median structure.
A: Max-heap for low half, min-heap for high half, sizes differ by at most 1.

---

Q: Sliding-window max data structure.
A: Monotonic deque of indices with decreasing values.

---

Q: Why store indices in the sliding-window max deque?
A: Eviction at the window edge needs to know whether the front index expired.

---

Q: Algorithm R reservoir replacement rule.
A: For item index `i >= k`, draw `j = randrange(i + 1)` and replace slot `j` if `j < k`.

---

Q: Reservoir sampling survival probability after `n` items.
A: Every item is kept with probability `k/n`.

---

Q: Misra-Gries memory and guarantee.
A: `k - 1` counters; undercount at most `n/k`; every item with frequency `> n/k` survives.

---

Q: Count-Min sketch dimensions.
A: Width `ceil(e/eps)`, depth `ceil(ln(1/delta))`.

---

Q: Count-Min bias direction.
A: It overestimates only.

---

Q: HyperLogLog standard error.
A: About `1.04 / sqrt(m)` for `m` registers.

---

Q: HLL with `2^14` registers costs and error.
A: About 12 KiB and about 0.8% relative error.

---

Q: Bloom filter error side.
A: False positives only, never false negatives.

---

Q: Bloom filter cost at 1% false positives.
A: About 9.6 bits per element and about 7 hash probes.

---

Q: What does SWAG support?
A: Sliding-window aggregates for any associative operation without needing an inverse.

---

Q: Event time vs processing time.
A: Event time is when the event happened; processing time is when the system observed it.

---

Q: What is a watermark?
A: A heuristic claim that no events older than time `W` are still expected.

---

Q: Kafka ordering guarantee.
A: Ordering is per partition only.

---

Q: Exactly-once processing requires what three pieces?
A: Replayable source, snapshotted state, and idempotent or transactional sink.
